    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-11-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-11-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="317"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d317">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.12/1662: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McGurk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-11-21T10:00:00-06:00"
                            >November 21, 1941—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:42 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>642. The press reacted enthusiastically at the signing of the agreements in
                    Washington. President Avila Camacho stated “this is a great event in the
                    friendship between Mexico and the United States of America and not only for them
                    but also for all the countries of the Americas. It confirms the Good Neighbor
                    policy”. Padilla in a longer statement said in effect that the conclusion of the
                    agreements marks a new milestone in the history of Mexican-American relations;
                    that it shows that Mexico knows how to perform its international <pb facs="0406"
                        n="398" xml:id="pg_398"/> duties while maintaining all of its rights of
                    sovereignty; that Mexico and the United States are practising a policy of
                    inter-American good neighborliness and of solidarity in the defense of
                    democratic institutions; that the settlement of outstanding questions between
                    the two countries will permit a better and more intimate solidarity between the
                    two peoples and will promote intense and just friendship between them which is
                    in accordance with their destinies.</p>
                <p>Editorial comments will be forwarded by air mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McGurk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
